The Google Maps Time Travel API doesn't exist per se; instead, Google provides various endpoints through the Maps APIs that may relate to geographic information, directions, and imagery, but it does not offer a dedicated "time travel" endpoint to browse historical maps or change the time of viewing.

However, you can access historical imagery through the Google Earth Engine or possibly through the Google Street View API for virtual tours, but it's important to note that this doesn't represent "time travel" in a typical sense.

Here’s a basic example of how to use the Google Maps JavaScript API to show a street view, assuming you want to view current locations. If you are looking for historical images or some time-based context, the Street View API can be used to get imagery from specific dates when available.

### Example of Google Maps JavaScript API

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Simple Google Maps Street View</title>
    <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY"></script>
    <style>
        #map {
            height: 100vh;
            width: 100%;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="map"></div>
    <script>
        function initMap() {
            // Specify the location you want to show in Street View
            var location = {lat: 37.3318, lng: -122.0312}; // Example location

            var map = new google.maps.Map(document.getElementById('map'), {
                center: location,
                zoom: 14
            });

            var panorama = new google.maps.StreetViewPanorama(
                document.getElementById('map'), {
                    position: location,
                    pov: {
                        heading: 165,
                        pitch: 0
                    },
                    zoom: 1,
                    visible: true,
                    // Example usage of a date parameter if supported (check API docs for details)
                    date: '2022-01' // Adjust based on API capabilities
                });

            map.setStreetView(panorama);
        }

        // initialize the map when the page loads
        window.onload = initMap;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Notes:
- Replace `YOUR_API_KEY` with your actual Google Maps API key.
- The example above sets up a Google Map and displays a Street View panorama.
- You must check [Google's documentation](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/streetview) for the latest updates on features and API capabilities, as well as any historical imagery features.
- For historical imagery, Google Earth Engine and other databases may be more useful but involve complex API interactions not covered in simple JavaScript API usage.

For access to historical images and more complex usage, consider querying Google APIs that deal with geographic data or satellite imagery, as this will require more advanced handling on your part.

